baseline_groups.claim_summary: NSP treatment improves economic welfare as measured by the Anderson economic index (male respondents).
baseline_groups.notes: Primary economic outcome. Not significant (p=0.226). Most robustness checks target this outcome.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: NSP treatment improves public goods provision as measured by the Anderson public goods index.
baseline_groups.notes: Significant (p=0.017). One heterogeneity robustness spec targets this outcome.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: NSP treatment improves subjective economic perceptions.
baseline_groups.notes: Highly significant (p<1e-11). One heterogeneity robustness spec targets this outcome.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: NSP treatment improves attitudes toward government.
baseline_groups.notes: Significant (p<0.001). One heterogeneity robustness spec targets this outcome.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: NSP treatment improves perceived security (male and female respondents).
baseline_groups.notes: Both male and female perceived security baselines are significant. Rows 51-52 are exact duplicates of rows 5-6 under baseline/security/ prefix.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: NSP treatment affects experienced security incidents.

global_notes: This paper evaluates NSP across multiple outcome domains (economic, public goods, attitudes, security). 10 baseline rows, 3 are exact duplicates (rows 51-53 repeat rows 5-7). Bulk of robustness specs target G1 economic index. Heterogeneity specs (15/71 rows) are substantial. Five placebo tests use pre-treatment security incidents. Some FE variation specs (Village FE, no FE) change the estimand fundamentally from the matched-pairs design.
